(un)Phantasmist of CoFE<BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ugulorgularin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gulor Gularin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Board Veteran</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(6/13/02 6:20:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1490.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: OK</span><hr size=1> Personally I think this guy was almost assuredly here to do damage. That being said, he should have been monitored closely and followed to see what other agents he would have come in contact with. In the course of his activities he sooner or later would have tried to build a bomb of some sort or done something else that he could be charged with. Once he is caught red handed, he should have been charged with treason. If he was just doing recon, he could still have been nabbed for questioning before he tried to leave the country again.<br>
<br>
This &quot;enemy combatant&quot; stuff sounds entirely too shady to me. It might be strictly legal, but I sure as hell don't like the implications. Suppose some guy has a flat tire on the highway and you help him out. The FBI happens to be following the guy and gets lots of pictures of you helping him fix a flat. The next day he is caught trying to bomb a gas station. Lo and behold you are picked up , labeled an enemy combatant because they have pictures of you helping him on the highway and you are locked away with no lawyer, no charges and no recourse for months or even years on end. Far fetched? Yes, but not impossible. That is what I have a problem with. <p>Gulor Gularin
